reviews.review_text:
Spoiled Rotten I'll keep this short and sweet:

Top Notch Show + Seamons Matrix = Ridiculousness

Just push play.  You won't regret it.
Better yet... Better yet, download it here: http://bt.etree.org/details.php?id=523148

great music/sad song choices If you look at the song choices they are full of the saddest ones the dead play...  Loser is so melancholy, early West LA is mournful (nice ginger verse),  Looks like rain: "rain, rain go away." Soulful He's Gone...

Anyway not bad at all, in fact i love it, a nice slice of of the emotional kaleidoscope that the dead bring us.  I think it is interesting to note the predominance of the sad; I did bit of research and can't find any deaths, or other abnormal sad things going on in dead history at this time.  I am probably missing something though...

Any ideas?
Peak early 80's The god damn grateful dead are here

1st and BEST! This 1st set was the first of hundreds of bootleg tapes I recieved. I got a copy from Lou Terzini of the Berklee College of Music band, "The Electric Rainbow Church" in 10/84. One of the best boots....RIP Lou!!!!!.......
Mike "The Ice-Man" Angelucci  3/24//10  Philly!
Crackling with energy This was my first trip to the big apple to see the Dead...What an awesome show, right from the get go ..Truly amazing!! hard to belive it was 28 years ago...Times flying

Playing In The Band! I'm making a point to review every MSG show I attended from this point on. From 1981 on I saw everyone of them.  My reviews will only be posted on what I believe to be the best recording of the concert. Don't care much for audience tapes but I do like a good matrix board  and on occasion a very good audience recording due to no soundboard being available for a performance. Now with all that being said, I will reiterate what most previous reviewers below have stated. This show smokes from start to finish. The PITB starter sets the tone ( Jerry's fingers are like liquid lightning!) and the Good Lovin raps things up nicely. Great versions of all songs all around. Great matrix recording. Pitch level seems right and everybody can be heard clearly in the mix. I also love 1982 very much and it's hard to find a good soundboard from this year. For that reason alone I give this recording a 5 and another 5 for the performance.

Name, address & phone number~~Lord, and just how far to go Great Hunter Seamons Matrix + NYC + Hot show = Pure Bliss~!!! Within you will find the Ways & Means...Give It A Whirl>Forever Grateful>Forever Dead

Hunter Seamons = Genius How do you nominate someone for a MacArthur Fellowship? 
Hunter Seamons deserves it.

MSG shows were usually very good, this one was truly great! I attended this one and just re-listened lately. One of the best part of some of the GD concerts was when they really surprised us by playing a song in an unusual spot. This one started out of the gate with a really nice surprise, Playing in the Band, followed by Crazy Fingers! The garden crowd loved, it , and the first set took off from there. The latter part of the first set to me was huge, the LL Rain ( I admit I am a fan of the song) featured an unusual second lead from Jerry, which pushed the band - this is an all time great version. And is there really any better way to end the first set than China- Rider ? Well perhaps Scarlet -Fire, ( see 4/23/77, my favorite GD show attended), but ending the first set with this China Rider was truly special. Second set is no slouch, nice Throwin Stones - NFA in its earlier chosen spot , out of space. All in all a very satisfying night at the Garden!

Yet another superior fall '82 show luv the high time, estimated sequence with some big time first rate jamming on estimated w/ entire band locked in -- you can feel MSG about to explode as the band careens into estimated outro and bob doing his thing...
Outstanding What else to say? I have the official release but I keep coming back to the Seamons matrix. Just so damn good, and the show? Fuggetaboutit.
